{"title_page": "Granville Coghlan", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n|                   name = G B Coghlan\n|                  image = \n|                caption =\n|              birth_name = Granville Boyle Coghlan\n|               nickname =\n|           birth_place = [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle]], Sussex, England\n|           death_place =<ref>Noonan, Barry, comp.. London, England, Death Notices from The Times, 1982\u20131988 [database on-line]. Provo, UT, USA: The Generations Network, Inc., 2005. Original data: The Times. London, England: The Times, 1982\u20131988.</ref>\n|                 height =\n|                 weight =\n|            ru_position = [[lock (rugby union)|lock]]\n|        ru_amateuryears =\n|        ru_amateurclubs = [[Cambridge University RUFC]]\n|          ru_amclubcaps =\n|        ru_amclubpoints =\n|            ru_amupdate =\n|        ru_nationalteam = {{flagicon|GBR}}[[British and Irish Lions|British Isles]]\n|       ru_nationalyears = 1927\n|        ru_nationalcaps = 2\n|      ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n|            ru_ntupdate =\n|          ru_coachclubs =\n|          ru_coachyears =\n|         ru_coachupdate =\n|                  other =\n|             occupation = Teacher\n|                 spouse = Eileen He\u00fcckendorff\n|               children = Terence\n|              relatives =\n|                 school = [[Rugby School]]\n|             university = [[Clare College, Cambridge]]\n|                    website =\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1907|01|06|df=yes}}\n| death_date={{death date and age|1983|08|18|1907|01|06|df=yes}}\n}}\n'''Granville Boyle Coghlan''' was an educationalist and an early twentieth century rugby union international who is known as one of the \"lost lions\"<ref>David Walmsley (Author), Robby Elson (Editor), The Lions: The Complete History of the British and Irish Rugby Union Team, Genesis Publications (2005) {{ISBN|0-904351-96-3}}</ref> due to his participation on the [[1927 British Lions tour to Argentina]] which, although retrospectively recognised as a [[British & Irish Lions|Lions]] tour, did not confer test status on any of the four encounters with the [[Argentina national rugby union team]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nGranville B Coghlan was born on 6 January 1907<ref name=\"Cric\"/> in [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle]]. He was the elder son of Henry Granville Coghlan and Amy Fiennes Coghlan (n\u00e9e Twisleton)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=OwOcMdKz5lE6ED3eJ8exeg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 30 November 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> and had a younger brother Henry Patrick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=ttn5QafhZl8CqTjTpzi9UQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 30 November 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> His father was a teacher who hailed from Lancashire, himself the son of a clergyman. Henry, on moving to the Hastings area where he was married, founded a school, known as Seafield School, of which he became the headmaster. Granville's mother, Amy, was raised in [[Giggleswick]] near [[Settle, North Yorkshire|Settle]] in Yorkshire. She carried the middle name Fiennes, in common with a number of her relations. Combined with her maiden surname Twisleton, this carried the heavy implication that she was related to the Twiselton-Fiennes-Wycham family, the holders of the [[Twisleton-Wykeham-Fiennes baronets|Baronetcy of Banbury]], the current incumbent being Sir [[Ranulph Fiennes]]. The link is not fully established, although the Twiselton from whom the Baronet has inherited the name was himself from Yorkshire. What is certain is that Amy's forefather, Francis Twiselton was known as a giant of a man, standing 7'3''. His stature was recorded to have passed down the generations, and may have contributed to Granville's height and weight making him ideal for the rugby union position of lock.\n\nGranville attended [[Rugby School]]<ref>A. T. Michell, George Higginbotham, ''Rugby School register, Volume 4'', Rugby School,  \u2013 Education \u2013 1929, Page 554</ref> where he played both rugby and cricket.<ref name=\"Cric\">[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/289/289833/289833.html Granville Boyle Coghlan at cricketarchive.com]</ref>\n\n===Rugby career===\nHe went on to [[Clare College, Cambridge]]<ref>''Cambridge University List of Members Up to 31 December 1988'', (Cambridge University Press), 1989, {{ISBN|0-521-38237-8}}</ref> and was awarded a [[Cambridge University R.U.F.C.|rugby blue]]. It was from Cambridge that he was selected for the 1927 tour to Argentina. On this tour he was one of a number of uncapped players who was selected to play against the Argentina national side. He played in two of the four tests. Despite being selected for the Great Britain side, he never went on to play for his national side, England.\n\n===Education===\nAfter finishing his education, Granville followed his father's footsteps, becoming a teacher and went on to become the headmaster of the Seafield School. In turn, his son Terence became the headmaster until the school's closure.\n\nSeafield School was a school for boys aged between 8 and 13. It was located on Collington Lane West, one of three schools on the lane the others being Falconbury, also a boys' school and Effingham, for girls. These three schools were visited by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] in the 1960s. Seafield itself was used as quarters for a Canadian Anti Aircraft Battery that was serving in defence of Bexhill and Cooden Beach during the [[Second World War]]. Seafield and its two counterparts were closed in the early 1970s to open up land to be used for building new homes. However, their crests were preserved in a specially dedicated stained-glass window in the nearby St Mark's church of the parish of [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]]. The installation and dedication of the Seafield School memorial window happened in June 1963 and was dedicated to Henry Granville Coghlan, the founder of the school, and his wife Amy and son Patrick.<ref>East Sussex Record Office, ''Records deposited by the churchwardens on 5 April 1994 (ACC 6287) and by the incumbent and PCC on 6 October 1994 (ACC 6484)'' PAR245/10/2/44 and PAR245/3/2/3</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nIn 1932, Granville married Eileen He\u00fcckendorff<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=lMGTsPQ8LGKmRSxP6GhOWA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 1 December 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> and their eldest son, Terence Granville, was born in May 1934.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=a%2B%2BbYJWxFIo0IHTauNgsRA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 1 December 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> Terence died on 2 October 2009 in Weybridge UK. He leaves his wife Beverley, sons Simon Granville Gregory Coghlan, Robin Patrick Coghlan, Anthony Coghlan and his daughter, Nicola Scrivener.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{British and Irish Lions 1927}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coghlan, Granville}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:British and Irish Lions rugby union players from England]]\n[[Category:Cambridge University R.U.F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n|                   name = G B Coghlan\n|                  image = \n|                caption =\n|              birth_name = Granville Boyle Coghlan\n|               nickname =\n|           birth_place = [[Battle]], Sussex, England\n|           death_place =<ref>Noonan, Barry, comp.. London, England, Death Notices from The Times, 1982\u20131988 [database on-line]. Provo, UT, USA: The Generations Network, Inc., 2005. Original data: The Times. London, England: The Times, 1982\u20131988.</ref>\n|                 height =\n|                 weight =\n|            ru_position = [[lock (rugby union)|lock]]\n|        ru_amateuryears =\n|        ru_amateurclubs = [[Cambridge University RUFC]]\n|          ru_amclubcaps =\n|        ru_amclubpoints =\n|            ru_amupdate =\n|        ru_nationalteam = {{flagicon|GBR}}[[British and Irish Lions|British Isles]]\n|       ru_nationalyears = 1927\n|        ru_nationalcaps = 2\n|      ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n|            ru_ntupdate =\n|          ru_coachclubs =\n|          ru_coachyears =\n|         ru_coachupdate =\n|                  other =\n|             occupation = Teacher\n|                 spouse = Eileen He\u00fcckendorff\n|               children = Terence\n|              relatives =\n|                 school = [[Rugby School]]\n|             university = [[Clare College, Cambridge]]\n|                    website =\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1907|01|06|df=yes}}\n| death_date={{death date and age|1983|08|18|1907|01|06|df=yes}}\n}}\n'''Granville Boyle Coghlan''' was an educationalist and an early twentieth century rugby union international who is known as one of the \"lost lions\"<ref>David Walmsley (Author), Robby Elson (Editor), The Lions: The Complete History of the British and Irish Rugby Union Team, Genesis Publications (2005) {{ISBN|0-904351-96-3}}</ref> due to his participation on the [[1927 British Lions tour to Argentina]] which, although retrospectively recognised as a [[British & Irish Lions|Lions]] tour, did not confer test status on any of the four encounters with the [[Argentina national rugby union team]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nGranville B Coghlan was born on 6 January 1907<ref name=\"Cric\"/> in [[Battle]]. He was the elder son of Henry Granville Coghlan and Amy Fiennes Coghlan (n\u00e9e Twisleton)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=OwOcMdKz5lE6ED3eJ8exeg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 30 November 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> and had a younger brother Henry Patrick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=ttn5QafhZl8CqTjTpzi9UQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 30 November 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> His father was a teacher who hailed from Lancashire, himself the son of a clergyman. Henry, on moving to the Hastings area where he was married, founded a school, known as Seafield School, of which he became the headmaster. Granville's mother, Amy, was raised in [[Giggleswick]] near [[Settle, North Yorkshire|Settle]] in Yorkshire. She carried the middle name Fiennes, in common with a number of her relations. Combined with her maiden surname Twisleton, this carried the heavy implication that she was related to the Twiselton-Fiennes-Wycham family, the holders of the [[Twisleton-Wykeham-Fiennes baronets|Baronetcy of Banbury]], the current incumbent being Sir [[Ranulph Fiennes]]. The link is not fully established, although the Twiselton from whom the Baronet has inherited the name was himself from Yorkshire. What is certain is that Amy's forefather, Francis Twiselton was known as a giant of a man, standing 7'3''. His stature was recorded to have passed down the generations, and may have contributed to Granville's height and weight making him ideal for the rugby union position of lock.\n\nGranville attended [[Rugby School]]<ref>A. T. Michell, George Higginbotham, ''Rugby School register, Volume 4'', Rugby School,  \u2013 Education \u2013 1929, Page 554</ref> where he played both rugby and cricket.<ref name=\"Cric\">[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/289/289833/289833.html Granville Boyle Coghlan at cricketarchive.com]</ref>\n\n===Rugby career===\nHe went on to [[Clare College, Cambridge]]<ref>''Cambridge University List of Members Up to 31 December 1988'', (Cambridge University Press), 1989, {{ISBN|0-521-38237-8}}</ref> and was awarded a [[Cambridge University R.U.F.C.|rugby blue]]. It was from Cambridge that he was selected for the 1927 tour to Argentina. On this tour he was one of a number of uncapped players who was selected to play against the Argentina national side. He played in two of the four tests. Despite being selected for the Great Britain side, he never went on to play for his national side, England.\n\n===Education===\nAfter finishing his education, Granville followed his father's footsteps, becoming a teacher and went on to become the headmaster of the Seafield School. In turn, his son Terence became the headmaster until the school's closure.\n\nSeafield School was a school for boys aged between 8 and 13. It was located on Collington Lane West, one of three schools on the lane the others being Falconbury, also a boys' school and Effingham, for girls. These three schools were visited by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] in the 1960s. Seafield itself was used as quarters for a Canadian Anti Aircraft Battery that was serving in defence of Bexhill and Cooden Beach during the [[Second World War]]. Seafield and its two counterparts were closed in the early 1970s to open up land to be used for building new homes. However, their crests were preserved in a specially dedicated stained-glass window in the nearby St Mark's church of the parish of [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]]. The installation and dedication of the Seafield School memorial window happened in June 1963 and was dedicated to Henry Granville Coghlan, the founder of the school, and his wife Amy and son Patrick.<ref>East Sussex Record Office, ''Records deposited by the churchwardens on 5 April 1994 (ACC 6287) and by the incumbent and PCC on 6 October 1994 (ACC 6484)'' PAR245/10/2/44 and PAR245/3/2/3</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nIn 1932, Granville married Eileen He\u00fcckendorff<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=lMGTsPQ8LGKmRSxP6GhOWA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 1 December 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> and their eldest son, Terence Granville, was born in May 1934.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=a%2B%2BbYJWxFIo0IHTauNgsRA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate= 1 December 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> Terence died on 2 October 2009 in Weybridge UK. He leaves his wife Beverley, sons Simon Granville Gregory Coghlan, Robin Patrick Coghlan, Anthony Coghlan and his daughter, Nicola Scrivener.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{British and Irish Lions 1927}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coghlan, Granville}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:British and Irish Lions rugby union players from England]]\n[[Category:Cambridge University R.U.F.C. players]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix placename links, replaced:Battle\u2192Battle(2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Granville_Coghlan"}
{"title_page": "Jungle (band)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Jungle (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jungle\n| image            = JUNGLE -Rock wide.jpg\n| caption          = Jungle. From left to right: Tom McFarland, George Day, Rudi Salmon, Nat Zangi, Dominic Whalley, Josh Lloyd-Watson and Fraser MacColl\n| image_size       = 250px\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[London]], [[England]]\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[neo soul]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = [[XL Recordings|XL]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| current_members  = * Josh Lloyd-Watson\n* Tom McFarland\n* Fraser MacColl\n* George Day\n* Dominic Whalley\n* Rudi Salmon\n* Andro\n| past_members     = * Nat Zangi\n| website          = {{url|junglejunglejungle.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Jungle''' is an [[English people|English]] modern soul [[musical collective]] founded in 2013 by Tom McFarland and Josh Lloyd-Watson. Since its founding, Jungle has released two albums, 2014's ''Jungle'', which was shortlisted for the [[Mercury Prize]] that year, and 2018's ''For Ever''. The group is based in [[London]].\n\n==Background==\nJungle was founded by Tom McFarland and Josh Lloyd-Watson.<ref name=\"han\">{{cite web|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2014/06/23/jungle-music-collective |title= Jungle: A British Music Collective With Disco Beats|publisher=Here & Now |date=23 June 2014 |accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> The pair had been friends since they were nine years old, where they lived next door to each other in [[Shepherds Bush, London]].<ref name=\"esquire\">{{cite web |url=http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/music/6606/everything-you-need-to-know-about-jungle/ |title=Everything You Need To Know About Britain's Hottest Band |publisher=Esquire |date=2 July 2014 |accessdate=9 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227180601/http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/music/6606/everything-you-need-to-know-about-jungle/ |archive-date=27 December 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They went on to form Jungle at the beginning of 2013, choosing to put an aesthetic emphasis on the music\u2019s surrounding artwork and videos, and not on the pairs' own identity, (McFarland and Lloyd-Watson came to be known as T and J).<ref name=\"passionoftheweiss\">{{cite web|url=http://www.passionweiss.com/2014/03/12/question-in-the-form-of-an-answer-an-interview-with-jungle|title=Interview With Jungle |publisher=Passion of the Weiss |date=12 March 2014 |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref> Throughout the following year Jungle developed its nature as a collective by working with different artists across diverse disciplines. To perform the music live, Jungle expanded to a seven-piece band, fronted by J and T. The pair wished to challenge themselves, resisting the temptation to simply re-produce their music from their laptops, and instead translated their songs into a full and organic live experience. J and T have explained that Jungle stemmed from a desire for \u2018honesty\u2026 true connection and friendship. It\u2019s about being in a collective and collective energy\u2026 [a] team spirit.\u2019 <ref name=\"\u201cpigeonsandplanes\">{{cite web|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/2014/06/interview-jungle-on-friendship-self-censorship-and-the-mystery-that-they-never-intended/\n|title=Interview Jungle |publisher=Pigeons and Planes |date=12 June 2014 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\nJungle's musical style has been described as \"midtempo 1970s-style funk\"<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite web|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/03/12/sxsw-2014-jungle-unmasked-sort-of/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |title=SXSW 2014: Jungle Unmasked, Sort Of |publisher=ArtsBeat: NYTimes.com |date=12 March 2014 |accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> and their music is intermixed with \"tropical percussion, wildlife noises, falsetto yelps, psychedelic washes and badoinking bass\" <ref name=\"\u201cesquire\">{{cite web |url=http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/music/6606/everything-you-need-to-know-about-jungle/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |title=Everything You Need To Know About Britain\u2019s Hottest Band |publisher=Esquire |date=1 July 2014 |accessdate=9 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110151033/http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/music/6606/everything-you-need-to-know-about-jungle/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The band has a fearsome live reputation: \"Jungle are a spectacular live band,\" say DIY.<ref name=\"DIY\">{{cite web|url=https://diymag.com/2014/11/05/jungle-shepherds-bush-empire-london?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |title=Jungle Shepherd\u2019s Bush Empire |publisher=DIY |date=30 October 2014 |accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013\u20132018: ''Jungle'' ===\nJungle released their single \"The Heat\" on 21 October 2013 through Chess Club Records.<ref name=\"nme1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/jungle-the-uks-most-mysterious-act-finally-come-out-of-the-shadows |title=Jungle - The UK's Most Mysterious Act Finally Come Out Of The Shadows |publisher=NME |date=8 October 2013 |accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref> In December 2013, Jungle were nominated for [[BBC]]'s [[Sound of...|Sound of 2014]] prize.<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/ct3HSWD3sLlVTXjWwKQxlG/jungle |title=Sound of, 2014 - Jungle |publisher=BBC |date=2 December 2013 |accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref> That year, the group played at [[South by Southwest]] in Texas in March 2014.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" /> On 16 June 2014, the band played on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]],<ref name=\"\u201cxlrecordings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xlrecordings.com/news/watchtimeandbusyearninliveonjimmykimmel?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |title=Watch Time Live On Jimmy Kimmel |publisher=XL Recordings |date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=17 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110151533/http://www.xlrecordings.com/news/watchtimeandbusyearninliveonjimmykimmel?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |archivedate=10 November 2014 }}</ref> and played [[Glastonbury Festival 2014|Glastonbury Festival]] later that month.<ref name=\"bbc2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/errnc8/acts/ahf4wh#p021j4t1 |title=BBC Glastonbury 2014, Acts, Jungle |publisher=BBC |date=27 June 2014 |accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nTheir debut album ''[[Jungle (Jungle album)|Jungle]]'' was released through [[XL Recordings]] on 14 July 2014. To celebrate the release, the band played a special launch party on a Peckham rooftop. The show was filmed using drones.<ref name=\"\u201cjungle\">{{cite web|url=http://junglejunglejungle.tumblr.com/post/91937074349/peckham-jungle-album-launch-thanks-to-all-who?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |title=Peckham Album Launch |publisher=Jungle |date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> During launch week the band played live sessions on BBC Radio 1, 2 and 6 Music.\n\nDuring August 2014, the band played Reading and Leeds Festivals. During September 2014, Jungle played live on [[Le Grand Journal (Canal+)]], played with Pharrell Williams at London's Roundhouse for the iTunes Festival, and played live on [[Later... with Jools Holland]].<ref name=\"\u201cbbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qMRLp7rkoZI?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 |title=Jungle Live on Jools |publisher=bbc |date=17 September 2014 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe album \"Jungle\" was shortlisted for the 2014 [[Mercury Prize]] in September 2014.<ref name=\"mercury\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mercuryprize.com/aoty/shortlist.php?Year=2014 |title=2014 Shortlist - Barclaycard Mercury Prize |publisher=Barclaycard Mercury Prize |date=10 September 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912223850/http://www.mercuryprize.com/aoty/shortlist.php?Year=2014 |archive-date=12 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"[[Busy Earnin']]\" was also voted in at Number 67 in the 2014 Triple J Hottest 100 Countdown in Australia.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn early 2015, it was announced that the band would perform at the Boston Calling Music Festival in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ollman|first1=Jonah|title=Boston Calling Announces May 2015 Lineup|url=http://soundofboston.com/boston-calling-announces-may-2015-lineup/|website=Sound of Boston|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> On 26 June 2015, Jungle played on the Other Stage at the 2015 Glastonbury Festival. On 9 December 2017, they performed as part of the line up of Tr\u00f3pico, a 3 day-long music festival in Acapulco, Mexico.\n\n==== Use of songs in media ====\nTheir song \"[[Busy Earnin']]\" has been featured in many television shows and other media. It is present in the playlists of ''[[FIFA 15]]'' and ''[[Forza Horizon 2]]'' and was featured in TV productions several times, e.g. in the opening sequence and credits for the ''[[Tales from the Borderlands]]'' episode \"Zer0 Sum\", as a background music in a bar in Season 2 Episode 6 of ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'' as well as in a club scene in German television series ''[[Tatort]]'' (episode 916: \"Der W\u00fcstensohn\"). Since the end of 2014, \"[[Busy Earnin']]\" has been the title song of the German TV show ''Mein bester Feind''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.prosieben.de/tv/mein-bester-feind/alle-ganzen-folgen-von-mein-bester-feind|title=Mein bester Feind - Alle ganzen Folgen von Mein bester Feind|date=2 January 2015|access-date=18 October 2017|language=de|website=Prosieben.de}}</ref> \n\nTheir 2014 song \"[[lucky I got what I want]]\" was also used in the 2016 film [[Nerve (2016 film)|''Nerve'']]\n\nOn 10 November 2016, their song \"Busy Earnin'\" was played as part of the background storyline for the Season 2 Episode 9 episode titled 'Black Friday' of [[Superstore]], and in April 2017 it was used for the Toyota Yaris Hybrid TV advert. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvadsongs.uk/toyota-yaris-hybrid-advert-new-energy-for-city/|title=TV Ad Songs|website=TV Ad songs|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 November 2016, their song \"Drops\" was played in the closing of the final scene of Season 1 Episode 9 of [[Queen Sugar]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n=== 2018\u2013Present: ''For Ever'' ===\nOn 8 May 2018, Jungle released two new singles, \"House in L.A.\" and \"Happy Man,\" on a 7-inch record, and on multiple digital music platforms.\n\nOn 22 September 2018, the band played their single \"Heavy, California \"on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]] and, on 11 December 2018, the band played their single \"Smile\" on [[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Jimmy Kimmel Live|title=Jungle - Heavy, California|date=22 September 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ydTGmLs8ihs|access-date=10 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=The Late Show with Stephen Colbert|title=Jungle Perform 'Smile'|date=11 December 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_BGVa18vm7M|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Use of songs in media ====\nOn 13 September 2018, their single \"Heavy, California\" was used to open the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] September event.<ref>{{Citation|last=Apple|title=September Event 2018 \u2014 Apple|date=13 September 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wFTmQ27S7OQ|access-date=10 November 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, the band's single Platoon was used for the Peloton Digital Commercial <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s_7ro26_shw |title=YouTube |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref> Their single \"Beat 54 (All Good Now)\" was featured in football video game by [[EA Sports]], ''[[FIFA 19]]''. Recently during the summer of 2019, Jungle\u2019s song, \"The Heat\", was played in Starbucks Nitro Cold Brew TV Commercial, 'Whoa Nitro' [[Starbucks]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} Their single \"Happy Man\" was also featured in a commercial by phone network O2 in 2019.\n\n=== Music videos ===\nJungle is known for their one-shot dance videos directed by Josh Lloyd-Watson, one-half of Jungle, who often works with the same dancers, choreographer, and cinematographer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/article/best-music-videos-2019.html|title=The Best Music Videos of 2019|last=Zadie|first=Mooj|date=2019-12-12|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:6em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"UKchart\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/10018/jungle/|title=JUNGLE - Full Official Chart History|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL]]<br><ref name=\"BEL\">{{cite web|url=http://ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jungle+%5BUK%5D |website=Ultratop|title=Discografie Jungle|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Tracklisten|DEN]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[SNEP|FRA]]<br><ref name=fr>{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jungle+%5BUK%5D |website=Lescharts.com|title=Jungle discography|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment|GER]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[MegaCharts|NED]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jungle+%5BUK%5D|title=Discografie Jungle|website=dutchcharts.nl|accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Swiss Hitparade|SWI]]<br/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://hitparade.ch/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jungle+%5BUK%5D |title=Discographie Jungle |website=hitparade.ch |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jungle/chart-history/billboard-200 |title=Jungle Chart History: Billboard 200 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Jungle (Jungle album)|Jungle]]''\n|\n*Released: 14 July 2014\n*Label: [[XL Recordings|XL]]\n| 7\n| 20\n| 21\n| 28\n| 42\n| 43\n| 42\n| 34\n| 22\n| 84\n|\n*UK: 100,000<ref name=occarticle>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/barclaycard-mercury-prize-2014-the-real-winners-revealed-3243/|title=Barclaycard Mercury Prize 2014: The real winners revealed|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref>\n|\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: Gold<ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards/search.aspx|title=BPI Certified Awards > Search|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[For Ever (Jungle album)|For Ever]]''\n|\n*Released: 14 September 2018<ref name=\"ForEver\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/jungle-announce-new-album-for-ever-share-new-songs-heavy-california-and-cherry-2359815|title=Jungle announce new album 'For Ever', share new songs 'Heavy, California' and \u2018Cherry' \u2013 listen|work=[[NME]]|date=26 July 2018|accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>\n*Label: XL\n| 10\n| 28<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/albums-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref>\n| 13\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 34\n| \u2014\n| 22\n| 56\n|\n|\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Single\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"UKchart\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Indie Chart|UK<br/>Indie]]<br/><ref>Peak chart positions on UK Indie Chart:\n*For \"Busy Earnin'\":{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/12/2014-03-15/ |title=2014-03-15 Top 40 Independent Singles Archive |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL]]<br><ref name=\"BEL\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[SNEP|FRA]]<br><ref name=fr/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Alternative Songs|US<br/>Alt.]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jungle/chart-history/alternative-songs|title=Jungle Chart History: Alternative Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Platoon\"\n| 2013\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Jungle''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Busy Earnin']]\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2014\n| \u2014\n| 19\n| 77\n| 118\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Time\" \n| 94\n| \u2014\n| 62\n| 163\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Heat\" \n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 62\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Happy Man\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2018\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 37\n| rowspan=\"5\"| ''For Ever''\n