{"title_page": "Valerio Piva", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Valerio Piva\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1958|7|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Ceresara]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n| updated        = \n}}\n'''Valerio Piva''' (born 5 July 1958) is an Italian former [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"ProCycling\">{{cite web |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/Valerio_Piva |title=Valerio Piva |accessdate=22 March 2015 |work=Pro Cycling Stats}}</ref> He rode in the [[1990 Tour de France]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|3908}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piva, Valerio}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Valerio Piva\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1958|7|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Ceresara]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n| updated        = \n}}\n'''Valerio Piva''' (born 5 July 1958) is an Italian former [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"ProCycling\">{{cite web |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/Valerio_Piva |title=Valerio Piva |accessdate=22 March 2015 |work=Pro Cycling Stats}}</ref> He rode in the [[1990 Tour de France]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|3908}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piva, Valerio}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valerio_Piva"}
{"title_page": "The Street (Derbyshire)", "text_new": "[[File:The Street Roman Road.jpg|thumb|Route of The Street Roman road between Derby and Manchester]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n'''The Street''' is the medieval name of the Roman road that ran across the high limestone plateau of central [[Derbyshire]] from the spa town of [[Buxton]] (Latin ''[[Aquae Arnemetiae]]'') southeast towards modern [[Derby]]. The line of the road can be traced from surviving features, confirmed by archaeology, from Buxton as far as [[Longcliffe]] just north of [[Brassington]]. It is believed that from Brassington the road ran eastwards to [[Wirksworth]] and there joined another road which crossed the Derwent at Milford and ran on the east bank of the Derwent and can be traced to the northern suburbs of Derby to [[Derventio (Little Chester)|Little Chester]], the site of the Roman settlement of ''Derventio''. The 1723 map of Brassington Moor shows The Street road from Buxton through [[Pikehall]] up to the Upper Harborough Field Gate, leading onto Manystones Lane & Brassington Lane towards Wirksworth (probable site of the Roman town ''Lutudarum''). In records from 1613 the road from Brassington to Wirksworth is called 'Highe Streete'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wirksworthromanproject.co.uk/download/i/mark_dl/u/4012767328/4635968015/TheStreet3ed.pdf|title=The Street: A re-evaluation of the Roman road from Wirksworth to Buxton|last=Anton Shone and Dean Smart|first=|date=27 January 2019|website=Wirksworth Roman Project|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hart|first=C R|title=The North Derbyshire Archaeological Survey|publisher=Derbyshire Archaeological Society|year=1984|isbn=|location=|pages=83-108}}</ref>\n\nThe Romans built farmsteads near the Street, to feed the soldiers and growing population in the area. Remains of a farm have been found near [[Minninglow]]. Excavations by Lomas at Minninglow in 1958 revealed the layered [[Agger (ancient Rome)|agger]] structure of the Roman road. The Street was recorded as 'Streete Way' in 1533 in the Bateman Manuscript, Chatsworth. On current OS maps there are many names related to The Street such as Street Farm, Street House Farm, Middle Street Farm and Straight (Street) Knolls Barn. There are documents from 963 AD and about 1223 that suggest The Street was previously known as King Street.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/2-the-romans-in-derbyshire-c2544.html The Romans in Derbyshire] Peak District Online</ref>[[File:Plaque near course of Buxton-to-Derby Roman Road (geograph 3759761).jpg|thumb|Plaque by Buxton to Derby Roman Road]]The plaque in the stone wall by The Street 'Buxton Derby' road near Arbor Low (at OS map location SK 1649 6232) is inscribed: \"Huius viae curam curatores viarum non susceperunt\". This translates as \"The road menders have not taken care of this road\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/3270628|title=Geograph:: A plaque in the wall (C) Peter Barr|website=www.geograph.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nNorth west of Buxton, the road west of the [[Upper Goyt Valley]] is called The Street.<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nThe course of the Roman road north from Buxton to [[Ardotalia|Melandra]] fort (near [[Glossop|Glossop)]] was identified in 1970. The agger of a Roman road (running due north to [[Dove Holes]] from the junction of [[Batham Gate]] Roman road with the A6 road) confirmed the observations of this route by Turner in 1903. Six other sections of road were identified by this field work and excavations. This allowed to route to be plotted running through [[Chapel-en-le-Frith]], [[Chapel Milton|Chapel Minton]], [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] and up to Cown Edge, to within 3 miles of Melandra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-2300-1/dissemination/pdf/091/DAJ_v091_1971_040-057.pdf|title=A ROMAN ROAD BETWEEN BUXTON AND MELANDRA CASTLE, GLOSSOP (Derbyshire Archaeological Journal 1971, Volume 91)|last=P. WROE and P. MELLOR|first=|date=1971|website=Archaeology Data Service|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* G. Guilbert, K. Challis, \"Excavations across the supposed line of 'the Street' Roman road south-east of Buxton, 1991\" in ''Derbyshire Archaeological Journal'' vol. 113 (1991) pp. 45-60\n* J. Lomas, \"Problems of the Roman Road between Buxton and Little Chester, Derby\" in ''Derbyshire Archaeological Journal'' vol. 78 (1958)\n* A. Shone and D. Smart, \"The Street: A re-evaluation of the Roman road from Wirksworth to Buxton\" (2017) [http://www.wirksworthromanproject.co.uk/ Wirksworth Archaeological Society] \n\n{{Derby Museum}}\n\n[[Category:Roman roads in England]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Roman Derby]]\n[[Category:Roads in Derbyshire]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Street}}\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:The Street Roman Road.jpg|thumb|Route of The Street Roman road between Derby and Manchester]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n'''The Street''' is the medieval name of the Roman road that ran across the high limestone plateau of central [[Derbyshire]] from the spa town of [[Buxton]] (Latin ''[[Aquae Arnemetiae]]'') southeast towards modern [[Derby]]. The line of the road can be traced from surviving features, confirmed by archaeology, from Buxton as far as [[Longcliffe]] just north of [[Brassington]]. It is believed that from Brassington the road ran eastwards to [[Wirksworth]] and there joined another road which crossed the Derwent at Milford and ran on the east bank of the Derwent and can be traced to the northern suburbs of Derby to [[Derventio (Little Chester)|Little Chester]], the site of the Roman settlement of ''Derventio''. The 1723 map of Brassington Moor shows The Street road from Buxton through [[Pikehall]] up to the Upper Harborough Field Gate, leading onto Manystones Lane & Brassington Lane towards Wirksworth (probable site of the Roman town ''Lutudarum''). In records from 1613 the road from Brassington to Wirksworth is called 'Highe Streete'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wirksworthromanproject.co.uk/download/i/mark_dl/u/4012767328/4635968015/TheStreet3ed.pdf|title=The Street: A re-evaluation of the Roman road from Wirksworth to Buxton|last=Anton Shone and Dean Smart|first=|date=27 January 2019|website=Wirksworth Roman Project|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hart|first=C R|title=The North Derbyshire Archaeological Survey|publisher=Derbyshire Archaeological Society|year=1984|isbn=|location=|pages=83-108}}</ref>\n\nThe Romans built farmsteads near the Street, to feed the soldiers and growing population in the area. Remains of a farm have been found near [[Minninglow]]. Excavations by Lomas at Minninglow in 1958 revealed the layered [[Agger (ancient Rome)|agger]] structure of the Roman road. The Street was recorded as 'Streete Way' in 1533 in the Bateman Manuscript, Chatsworth. On current OS maps there are many names related to The Street such as Street Farm, Street House Farm, Middle Street Farm and Straight (Street) Knolls Barn. There are documents from 963 AD and about 1223 that suggest The Street was previously known as King Street.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/2-the-romans-in-derbyshire-c2544.html The Romans in Derbyshire] Peak District Online</ref>[[File:Geograph-3759761-by-Graham-Hogg.jpg|thumb|Plaque by Buxton to Derby Roman Road]]The plaque in the stone wall by The Street 'Buxton Derby' road near Arbor Low (at OS map location SK 1649 6232) is inscribed: \"Huius viae curam curatores viarum non susceperunt\". This translates as \"The road menders have not taken care of this road\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/3270628|title=Geograph:: A plaque in the wall (C) Peter Barr|website=www.geograph.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nNorth west of Buxton, the road west of the [[Upper Goyt Valley]] is called The Street.<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nThe course of the Roman road north from Buxton to [[Ardotalia|Melandra]] fort (near [[Glossop|Glossop)]] was identified in 1970. The agger of a Roman road (running due north to [[Dove Holes]] from the junction of [[Batham Gate]] Roman road with the A6 road) confirmed the observations of this route by Turner in 1903. Six other sections of road were identified by this field work and excavations. This allowed to route to be plotted running through [[Chapel-en-le-Frith]], [[Chapel Milton|Chapel Minton]], [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] and up to Cown Edge, to within 3 miles of Melandra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-2300-1/dissemination/pdf/091/DAJ_v091_1971_040-057.pdf|title=A ROMAN ROAD BETWEEN BUXTON AND MELANDRA CASTLE, GLOSSOP (Derbyshire Archaeological Journal 1971, Volume 91)|last=P. WROE and P. MELLOR|first=|date=1971|website=Archaeology Data Service|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* G. Guilbert, K. Challis, \"Excavations across the supposed line of 'the Street' Roman road south-east of Buxton, 1991\" in ''Derbyshire Archaeological Journal'' vol. 113 (1991) pp. 45-60\n* J. Lomas, \"Problems of the Roman Road between Buxton and Little Chester, Derby\" in ''Derbyshire Archaeological Journal'' vol. 78 (1958)\n* A. Shone and D. Smart, \"The Street: A re-evaluation of the Roman road from Wirksworth to Buxton\" (2017) [http://www.wirksworthromanproject.co.uk/ Wirksworth Archaeological Society] \n\n{{Derby Museum}}\n\n[[Category:Roman roads in England]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Roman Derby]]\n[[Category:Roads in Derbyshire]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Street}}\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "name_user": "Bjh21", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Geograph-3759761-by-Graham-Hogg.jpg\u2192File:Plaque near course of Buxton-to-Derby Roman Road (geograph 3759761).jpgMore descriptive name (c:COM:FRcriterion 2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Street_(Derbyshire)"}
{"title_page": "15th Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name                     = 15th Anti-Aircraft Brigade\n| image                         = Koning_Soldaat.,_item_60.jpg\n| image_size                    = \n| caption                       = Cap badge of the [[Royal Artillery]] under [[King George VI]]\n| dates                         = 1941\u20141944\n| country                       = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch                        = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n*[[Royal Artillery]]\n| type                          = [[Anti-aircraft artillery]]\n| role                          = Anti-aircraft defence of [[Gibraltar]]\n| size                          = [[Brigade]]\n| command_structure             = \n| garrison                      = [[RAF Gibraltar]]\n| garrison_label                = Brigade Headquarters\n| battles                       = [[World War II]]\n*[[Military history of Gibraltar during World War II|Defence of Gibraltar]]\n| commander1                    = [[Duncan Learmonth]]\n| commander1_label              = [[Brigadier]]\n}}\n'''15th Anti-Aircraft Brigade''' (15th AA Bde) was an air defence formation of the [[Royal Artillery]] which saw service during the middle years of [[World War II]].  Before formation of the brigade, there were no official 'AA formations' on [[Gibraltar]], but this shortly changed following the [[Battle of France]].  The brigade continued to serve as the prime AA defence formation until it was disbanded in 1944.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:3.7 inch anti-aircraft gun at Napier of Magdala Battery, Gibraltar.jpg|thumb|252x252px|3.7 inch anti-aircraft gun at Napier of Magdala Battery, Gibraltar|alt=|left]]\n=== Background ===\nOn the outbreak of war in September 1939 there had only been two batteries (9 and 19 AA Btys) manning the totally inadequate AA defences of Gibraltar, which consisted of four old 3-inch guns and four new 3.7-inch guns, spread in two-gun sections to give the widest possible coverage, and two of the new Bofors 40 mm guns to protect the [[Gibdock|Royal Navy Dockyard]], with the assistance of [[Royal Navy]] (RN) [[QF 2-pounder naval gun#QF%202-pounder%20Mark%20VIII|2-pounder pom-pom guns]]. [[10th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|10th AA Rgt]] was formed in December 1939 to command 9 and 19 AA Btys and train the AA Section of the new [[Gibraltar Defence Force]] (GDF), which took over the 3-inch guns. Apart from occasional shots fired at unidentified aircraft penetrating Gibraltar's airspace, there were no attacks on the fortress during the '[[Phoney war]]' period.<ref>Routledge, Table XI, p. 68; Table XIII, p. 69.</ref><ref name=\":0\">Routledge, pp. 200-4.</ref><ref name=\"RA39\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page10.html|title=10 HAA Rgt at RA 39\u201345.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218082653/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page10.html|archive-date=2011-02-18|access-date=2011-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/124/2019/07/Gibraltar-Command-1939.pdf|title=Gibraltar Command Order of Battle (1939)|last=|first=|date=21 July 2019|website=britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://niehorster.org/017_britain/39_army/gibraltar.html|title=Gibraltar, 3 September 1939|last=|first=|date=4 December 2012|website=niehorster.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Battle of France|Fall of France]], a group of AA detachments under [[53rd (City of London) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|53rd (City of London) AA Rgt]] escaped from [[Marseilles]] aboard the SS ''Alma Dawson''. A French dockyard strike prevented them from loading any of their 3-inch guns or vehicles, but they mounted Bofors guns on the ship's deck and put to sea on 18 June. On arrival in Gibraltar they reinforced 10th AA Rgt. 82nd (Essex) AA Regiment arrived on 27 June, and once it had unloaded its guns and equipment 53rd AA Rgt re-embarked for home.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>53 HAA Regt War Diary 1940\u201341, [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives (TNA), Kew]], file WO 166/2343.</ref><ref name=\"Joslen552\">Joslen, pp. 552\u20133.</ref>\n\nThere followed a reorganisation of the AA units in Gibraltar: 19 AA Bty joined 82nd AA Rgt, together with the GDF HAA battery, while 9 AA Bty took over all the Bofors guns. A searchlight battery arrived, and an AA Operations Room (AAOR) was established to control all the gunsites and to coordinate with AA-equipped ships in the harbour. 10th AA Rgt HQ was ordered to be transferred to [[Malta]] in July, but this did not occur until November when, as part of [[Operation Coat]], a reinforcement convoy for Malta put in at Gibraltar and picked it up.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe first serious air raid on Gibraltar came at 02.00 on 18 July, when two unidentified aircraft bombed the slopes of the Rock, causing some fatalities. The attack was thought to be by the [[Vichy French Air Force]] in retaliation for the British attack on the French fleet at [[Mers-el-Kebir]] on 3 July ([[Attack on Mers-el-K\u00e9bir|Operation Catapult]]), which had been carried out by [[Force H]] from Gibraltar. On 21 August the AA defences brought down a [[Savoia-Marchetti SM.79]] bomber during a raid by the Italian ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]''. On 24 and 25 September waves of Vichy bombers attacked Gibraltar again in retaliation for the British and [[Free France|Free French]] attack on [[Dakar]] ([[Battle of Dakar|Operation Menace]]), and caused considerable damage. Several of these bombers were shot down by the combined AA fire. On other occasions the guns fired at single Italian reconnaissance aircraft, known to the garrison as 'Persistent Percy'.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Playfair, Vol I, pp. 130\u201337, 142.</ref><ref>Rankin, pp. 1\u20137.</ref><ref>Smith, pp. 57\u201388.</ref><ref name=\"Farn200\">Farndale, pp. 200\u20131.</ref><ref>Rankin, pp. 295\u20139.</ref>\n\n=== Formation ===\nDuring to the increase of raids and the coming [[North African Campaign]], the [[War Office]] (WO) approved the formation of a new AA Brigade which would handle the increasing demands brought on CRA, Gibraltar.  This new formation was to be known as the '''15th Anti-Aircraft Brigade''' (15th AA Bde) which was to take over all AA matters on the rock.  On 2 September 1941 the brigade was constituted with HQ based at [[RAF Gibraltar]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">Frederick, p. 1049.</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/124/2019/07/Gibraltar-Command-1942.pdf|title=Gibraltar Command Order of Battle (1942)|last=|first=|date=21 July 2019|website=britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>[[File:Gibraltar during the Second World War GM4392.jpg|thumb|The [[Gibraltar Defence Force]] training on a 3.7-inch gun.]]\nThe brigade was then organised as;<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">Routledge, Table XXXIV: Page 212.</ref>\n\n* Brigade Headquarters under [[Brigadier]] [[Duncan Learmonth|Duncan Alexander Learmonth]]<ref group=\"Notes\">Assigned directly by the Governor of Gibraltar in September 1941</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.generals.dk/general/Learmont/Duncan_Alexander/Great_Britain.html|title=Learmont, Duncan Alexander|last=|first=|date=|website=generals.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 142nd General Operation Post (Operations Room)\n*13th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery (Regular, composite) \u2014 ''raised in [[Gibraltar]] with composite AA units based there, later disbanded on 10 December 1942''\n** RHQ\n** 288th HAA Bty \u2014 ''from [[94th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|94th HAA Regt, RA]]''\n**[[Z Battery|1st Rocket AA Troop]], [[Royal Artillery]] (AA Rockets)\n** 1st Radar Detection Finding Bty, RA\n*[[82nd (Essex) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (TA)\n** RHQ\n** 156th, 193rd, and 256th HAA Btys\n**[[Gibraltar Defence Force|Gibraltar Defence Force HAA Bty, RA]]\n*[[3rd Light Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (Regular) \u2014 ''raised in [[Woolwich]] 2 September, arrived in [[Gibraltar]] on 27 September 1941''\n** RHQ\n** 9th, 114th, and 126th LAA Btys\n* 3rd Searchlight Bty, RA (Regular) \u2014 ''Formed 30 December 1939 in [[Gibraltar]], formally administered by the [[10th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|10th HAA Regt, RA]]''\n\n=== Gibraltar 'Blitz' ===\n[[File:The British Army on Gibraltar 1941 GM93.jpg|left|thumb|Mobile 3.7-inch HAA gun deployed at [[White Rock Battery]], November 1941.]]\n[[File:Searchlights on the Rock of Gibraltar, 1942.jpg|thumb|241x241px|Searchlights over [[Gibraltar]] during an air raid practice on 20 November 1942.]]\nAmong the many tasks facing 15th AA Brigade was the integration of AA fire in defence against sea or land invasion, in which it played an important part.  Equally important was the careful distribution of gun and radar positions to ensure the most effective converge from the increased firepower and the constant practice of day and night barrages, in which live firing was regularly employed and closely recorded, to eliminate errors and weak spots.  Aware of the vulnerability of positions to direct attack after opening fire, each AA position was given a 20mm Oerlikon for self-defence.  The basis of the plan for the revised layer was to bring the fire of 20 HAA gus to bear on a target travelling at 240 mph, approaching from any direction and at a typical height of 12,000 feet.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Routledge, Map 12: The Defence of Gibraltar July 1940</ref>\n\nIn January 1942, the [[Governor of Gibraltar]], [[General]] the Viscount [[John Vereker, 6th Viscount Gort]] (Lord Gort) wrote to the [[War Office]] asking for more HAA guns, preferably [[QF 5.25-inch naval gun#Land service|5.25 inch heavy AA guns]], for GLII sets with semi-automatic plotters and another 8 x [[Bofors 40 mm gun]] (LAA guns).  Part of this request was due to 15th AA Brigade's wish to provide the [[Gibraltar International Airport|North airfield]] with its own LAA defence; hitherto it had depended on the main layout for coverage.  Nothing was sent, however, other than 3-inch rockets and their launchers and the airfield received only a small deployment of [[20 mm Polsten]] and [[Bofors 40 mm gun|Bofors 40 mm guns]] together with some machine-guns, all withdrawn from other positions, and three searchlights.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDuring the whole of 1942 there were six bombing raids on Gibraltar, two of which were unidentified, and 18 reconnaissance overflights, all but two of them German. Four aircraft were shot down and others crash-landed in Spain. Some of the Italian raids missed their targets and dropped their bombs in Spanish territory, and Spanish AA guns sometimes opened fire as a raid passed towards them. By the end of 1942, the AA defences of Gibraltar reached a peak of scale and efficiency, but the threat had dwindled. There were only two or three reconnaissance flights during 1943.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"RA82\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page45.html|title=82 HAA Rgt at RA 39\u201345|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218063326/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page45.html|archive-date=2011-02-18|access-date=2011-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Joslen5522\">Joslen, pp. 552\u20133.</ref>\n\n=== Later Years ===\nIt was [[War Office]] policy that army units should be replaced after three years' service overseas.  Therefore, in accordance with this policy, the 13th, 82nd, and 3rd AA regts were removed, being replaced by the 175th and 141st.  This left, the brigade organised by May 1943, as:<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* Brigade HQ\n* 142nd General Operation Post (Operations Room)\n* [[175th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (Regular)\n** RHQ\n** 1st Range and Detection Finding (Radar) Battery\n**[[Z Battery|1st Anti-Aircraft 'Z' Troop, Royal Artillery]]\n** 375th, 386th, 441st, and 228th<ref group=\"Notes\">On 25 August, the battery was replaced by 596 HAA Bty, which moved 177th HAA Rgt.  The former was moved to [[82nd (Essex) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|82nd (Essex) HAA Rgt]].</ref> HAA Btys\n* [[141st Light Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (TA)\n** RHQ, 456th, 466th, and 467th LAA Btys\n* 3rd Searchlight Battery, RA\n\nBy 1944 the raids from the [[Luftwaffe]] had decreased following the [[Operation Overlord|Invasion of France]], and AA defences of the island were gradually rationalised until 19 February 1944 when brigade began to disband which was completed on 7 March.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"Notes\" />\n\n== Footnotes ==\n<references />\n\n== References ==\n\n* J.B.M. Frederick, ''Lineage Book of British Land Forces 1660-1978'', Volume II, [[Wakefield]], [[United Kingdom]]: Microform Academic Publishers, 1984 {{ISBN|1-85117-008-1}}.\n*[[Brigadier]] N. W. Routledge. ''History of the Royal Regiment of Artillery: Anti-Aircraft Artillery 1914-55''. (1994). [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]: Brassey's Publishing. {{ISBN|1-85753-099-3}}.\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] H. F. Joslen, ''Orders of Battle Second World War 1939-45'', Reprinted by permission of [[Her Majesty's Stationery Office]], [[Eastbourne]], [[United Kingdom]]. {{ISBN|9781843424741}}.\n* Martin Brayley, ''The British Army 1939-45 (2); Middle East & Mediterranean - Men-at-Arms Series''. 2002: Osprey Publishing, [[Botley, Oxfordshire|Botley]], [[Oxford]], [[United Kingdom]]. {{ISBN|1-84176-237-7}}.\n* Charles D. Pettibone, ''The Organisation and Order of Battle of Militaries in World War II, Volume II; The British Commonwealth''. 2006: Trafford Publishing, [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. {{ISBN|141208567-5}}.\n* Gen Sir [[Martin Farndale]], ''History of the Royal Regiment of Artillery: The Years of Defeat: Europe and North Africa, 1939\u20131941'', Woolwich: Royal Artillery Institution, 1988/London: Brasseys, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85753-080-2}}.\n* Nicholas Rankin, ''Defending the Rock: How Gibraltar Defeated Hitler'', London: Faber & Faber, 2017, {{ISBN|978-0-571-30770-8}}.\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1944]]\n[[Category:Air defence brigades of the British Army]]\n[[Category:Gibraltar]]\n[[Category:Gibraltar in World War II]]\n[[Category:Anti-Aircraft brigades of the British Army in World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name                     = 15th Anti-Aircraft Brigade\n| image                         = Koning_Soldaat.,_item_60.jpg\n| image_size                    = \n| caption                       = Cap badge of the [[Royal Artillery]] under [[King George VI]]\n| dates                         = 1941\u20141944\n| country                       = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch                        = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n*[[Royal Artillery]]\n| type                          = [[Anti-aircraft artillery]]\n| role                          = Anti-aircraft defence of [[Gibraltar]]\n| size                          = [[Brigade]]\n| command_structure             = \n| garrison                      = [[RAF Gibraltar]]\n| garrison_label                = Brigade Headquarters\n| battles                       = [[World War II]]\n*[[Military history of Gibraltar during World War II|Defence of Gibraltar]]\n| commander1                    = [[Duncan Learmonth]]\n| commander1_label              = [[Brigadier]]\n}}\n'''15th Anti-Aircraft Brigade''' (15th AA Bde) was an air defence formation of the [[Royal Artillery]] which saw service during the middle years of [[World War II]].  Before formation of the brigade, there were no official 'AA formations' on [[Gibraltar]], but this shortly changed following the [[Battle of France]].  The brigade continued to serve as the prime AA defence formation until it was disbanded in 1944.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:3.7 inch anti-aircraft gun at Napier of Magdala Battery, Gibraltar.jpg|thumb|252x252px|3.7 inch anti-aircraft gun at Napier of Magdala Battery, Gibraltar|alt=|left]]\n=== Background ===\nOn the outbreak of war in September 1939 there had only been two batteries (9 and 19 AA Btys) manning the totally inadequate AA defences of Gibraltar, which consisted of four old 3-inch guns and four new 3.7-inch guns, spread in two-gun sections to give the widest possible coverage, and two of the new Bofors 40 mm guns to protect the [[Gibdock|Royal Navy Dockyard]], with the assistance of [[Royal Navy]] (RN) [[QF 2-pounder naval gun#QF%202-pounder%20Mark%20VIII|2-pounder pom-pom guns]]. [[10th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|10th AA Rgt]] was formed in December 1939 to command 9 and 19 AA Btys and train the AA Section of the new [[Gibraltar Defence Force]] (GDF), which took over the 3-inch guns. Apart from occasional shots fired at unidentified aircraft penetrating Gibraltar's airspace, there were no attacks on the fortress during the '[[Phoney war]]' period.<ref>Routledge, Table XI, p. 68; Table XIII, p. 69.</ref><ref name=\":0\">Routledge, pp. 200-4.</ref><ref name=\"RA39\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page10.html|title=10 HAA Rgt at RA 39\u201345.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218082653/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page10.html|archive-date=2011-02-18|access-date=2011-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/124/2019/07/Gibraltar-Command-1939.pdf|title=Gibraltar Command Order of Battle (1939)|last=|first=|date=21 July 2019|website=britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://niehorster.org/017_britain/39_army/gibraltar.html|title=Gibraltar, 3 September 1939|last=|first=|date=4 December 2012|website=niehorster.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Battle of France|Fall of France]], a group of AA detachments under [[53rd (City of London) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|53rd (City of London) AA Rgt]] escaped from [[Marseilles]] aboard the SS ''Alma Dawson''. A French dockyard strike prevented them from loading any of their 3-inch guns or vehicles, but they mounted Bofors guns on the ship's deck and put to sea on 18 June. On arrival in Gibraltar they reinforced 10th AA Rgt. 82nd (Essex) AA Regiment arrived on 27 June, and once it had unloaded its guns and equipment 53rd AA Rgt re-embarked for home.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>53 HAA Regt War Diary 1940\u201341, [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives (TNA), Kew]], file WO 166/2343.</ref><ref name=\"Joslen552\">Joslen, pp. 552\u20133.</ref>\n\nThere followed a reorganisation of the AA units in Gibraltar: 19 AA Bty joined 82nd AA Rgt, together with the GDF HAA battery, while 9 AA Bty took over all the Bofors guns. A searchlight battery arrived, and an AA Operations Room (AAOR) was established to control all the gunsites and to coordinate with AA-equipped ships in the harbour. 10th AA Rgt HQ was ordered to be transferred to [[Malta]] in July, but this did not occur until November when, as part of [[Operation Coat]], a reinforcement convoy for Malta put in at Gibraltar and picked it up.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe first serious air raid on Gibraltar came at 02.00 on 18 July, when two unidentified aircraft bombed the slopes of the Rock, causing some fatalities. The attack was thought to be by the [[Vichy French Air Force]] in retaliation for the British attack on the French fleet at [[Mers-el-Kebir]] on 3 July ([[Attack on Mers-el-K\u00e9bir|Operation Catapult]]), which had been carried out by [[Force H]] from Gibraltar. On 21 August the AA defences brought down a [[Savoia-Marchetti SM.79]] bomber during a raid by the Italian ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]''. On 24 and 25 September waves of Vichy bombers attacked Gibraltar again in retaliation for the British and [[Free France|Free French]] attack on [[Dakar]] ([[Battle of Dakar|Operation Menace]]), and caused considerable damage. Several of these bombers were shot down by the combined AA fire. On other occasions the guns fired at single Italian reconnaissance aircraft, known to the garrison as 'Persistent Percy'.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Playfair, Vol I, pp. 130\u201337, 142.</ref><ref>Rankin, pp. 1\u20137.</ref><ref>Smith, pp. 57\u201388.</ref><ref name=\"Farn200\">Farndale, pp. 200\u20131.</ref><ref>Rankin, pp. 295\u20139.</ref>\n\n=== Formation ===\nDuring to the increase of raids and the coming [[North African Campaign]], the [[War Office]] (WO) approved the formation of a new AA Brigade which would handle the increasing demands brought on CRA, Gibraltar.  This new formation was to be known as the '''15th Anti-Aircraft Brigade''' (15th AA Bde) which was to take over all AA matters on the rock.  On 2 September 1941 the brigade was constituted with HQ based at [[RAF Gibraltar]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">Frederick, p. 1049.</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/124/2019/07/Gibraltar-Command-1942.pdf|title=Gibraltar Command Order of Battle (1942)|last=|first=|date=21 July 2019|website=britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>[[File:Gibraltar during the Second World War GM4392.jpg|thumb|The [[Gibraltar Defence Force]] training on a 3.7-inch gun.]]\nThe brigade was then organised as;<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">Routledge, Table XXXIV: Page 212.</ref>\n\n* Brigade Headquarters under [[Brigadier]] [[Duncan Learmonth|Duncan Alexander Learmonth]]<ref group=\"Notes\">Assigned directly by the Governor of Gibraltar in September 1941</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.generals.dk/general/Learmont/Duncan_Alexander/Great_Britain.html|title=Learmont, Duncan Alexander|last=|first=|date=|website=generals.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 142nd General Operation Post (Operations Room)\n*13th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery (Regular, composite) \u2014 ''raised in [[Gibraltar]] with composite AA units based there, later disbanded on 10 December 1942''\n** RHQ\n** 288th HAA Bty \u2014 ''from [[94th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|94th HAA Regt, RA]]''\n**[[Z Battery|1st Rocket AA Troop]], [[Royal Artillery]] (AA Rockets)\n** 1st Radar Detection Finding Bty, RA\n*[[82nd (Essex) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (TA)\n** RHQ\n** 156th, 193rd, and 256th HAA Btys\n**[[Gibraltar Defence Force|Gibraltar Defence Force HAA Bty, RA]]\n*[[3rd Light Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (Regular) \u2014 ''raised in [[Woolwich]] 2 September, arrived in [[Gibraltar]] on 27 September 1941''\n** RHQ\n** 9th, 114th, and 126th LAA Btys\n* 3rd Searchlight Bty, RA (Regular) \u2014 ''Formed 30 December 1939 in [[Gibraltar]], formally administered by the [[10th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|10th HAA Regt, RA]]''\n\n=== Gibraltar 'Blitz' ===\n[[File:The British Army on Gibraltar 1941 GM93.jpg|left|thumb|Mobile 3.7-inch HAA gun deployed at [[White Rock Battery]], November 1941.]]\n[[File:Searchlights on the Rock of Gibraltar, 1942.jpg|thumb|241x241px|Searchlights over [[Gibraltar]] during an air raid practice on 20 November 1942.]]\nAmong the many tasks facing 15th AA Brigade was the integration of AA fire in defence against sea or land invasion, in which it played an important part.  Equally important was the careful distribution of gun and radar positions to ensure the most effective converge from the increased firepower and the constant practice of day and night barrages, in which live firing was regularly employed and closely recorded, to eliminate errors and weak spots.  Aware of the vulnerability of positions to direct attack after opening fire, each AA position was given a 20mm Oerlikon for self-defence.  The basis of the plan for the revised layer was to bring the fire of 20 HAA gus to bear on a target travelling at 240 mph, approaching from any direction and at a typical height of 12,000 feet.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Routledge, Map 12: The Defence of Gibraltar July 1940</ref>\n\nIn January 1942, the [[Governor of Gibraltar]], [[General]] the Viscount [[John Vereker, 6th Viscount Gort]] (Lord Gort) wrote to the [[War Office]] asking for more HAA guns, preferably [[QF 5.25-inch naval gun#Land service|5.25 inch heavy AA guns]], for GLII sets with semi-automatic plotters and another 8 x [[Bofors 40 mm gun]] (LAA guns).  Part of this request was due to 15th AA Brigade's wish to provide the [[Gibraltar International Airport|North airfield]] with its own LAA defence; hitherto it had depended on the main layout for coverage.  Nothing was sent, however, other than 3-inch rockets and their launchers and the airfield received only a small deployment of [[20 mm Polsten]] and [[Bofors 40 mm gun|Bofors 40 mm guns]] together with some machine-guns, all withdrawn from other positions, and three searchlights.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDuring the whole of 1942 there were six bombing raids on Gibraltar, two of which were unidentified, and 18 reconnaissance overflights, all but two of them German. Four aircraft were shot down and others crash-landed in Spain. Some of the Italian raids missed their targets and dropped their bombs in Spanish territory, and Spanish AA guns sometimes opened fire as a raid passed towards them. By the end of 1942, the AA defences of Gibraltar reached a peak of scale and efficiency, but the threat had dwindled. There were only two or three reconnaissance flights during 1943.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"RA82\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page45.html|title=82 HAA Rgt at RA 39\u201345|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218063326/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/haa/page45.html|archive-date=2011-02-18|access-date=2011-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Joslen5522\">Joslen, pp. 552\u20133.</ref>\n\n=== Later Years ===\nIt was [[War Office]] policy that army units should be replaced after three years' service overseas.  Therefore, in accordance with this policy, the 13th, 82nd, and 3rd AA regts were removed, being replaced by the 175th and 141st.  This left, the brigade organised by May 1943, as:<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n* Brigade HQ\n* 142nd General Operation Post (Operations Room)\n* [[175th Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (Regular)\n** RHQ\n** 1st Range and Detection Finding (Radar) Battery\n**[[Z Battery|1st Anti-Aircraft 'Z' Troop, Royal Artillery]]\n** 375th, 386th, 441st, and 228th<ref group=\"Notes\">On 25 August, the battery was replaced by 596 HAA Bty, which moved 177th HAA Rgt.  The former was moved to [[82nd (Essex) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery|82nd (Essex) HAA Rgt]].</ref> HAA Btys\n* [[141st Light Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]] (TA)\n** RHQ, 456th, 466th, and 467th LAA Btys\n* 3rd Searchlight Battery, RA\n\nBy 1944 the raids from the [[Luftwaffe]] had decreased following the [[Operation Overlord|Invasion of France]], and AA defences of the island were gradually rationalised until 19 February 1944 when brigade began to disband which was completed on 7 March.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"Notes\" />\n\n== Footnotes ==\n<references />\n\n== References ==\n\n* J.B.M. Frederick, ''Lineage Book of British Land Forces 1660-1978'', Volume II, [[Wakefield]], [[United Kingdom]]: Microform Academic Publishers, 1984 {{ISBN|1-85117-008-1}}.\n*[[Brigadier]] N. W. Routledge. ''History of the Royal Regiment of Artillery: Anti-Aircraft Artillery 1914-55''. (1994). [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]: Brassey's Publishing. {{ISBN|1-85753-099-3}}.\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] H. F. Joslen, ''Orders of Battle Second World War 1939-45'', Reprinted by permission of [[Her Majesty's Stationary Office]], [[Eastbourne]], [[United Kingdom]]. {{ISBN|9781843424741}}.\n* Martin Brayley, ''The British Army 1939-45 (2); Middle East & Mediterranean - Men-at-Arms Series''. 2002: Osprey Publishing, [[Botley, Oxfordshire|Botley]], [[Oxford]], [[United Kingdom]]. {{ISBN|1-84176-237-7}}.\n* Charles D. Pettibone, ''The Organisation and Order of Battle of Militaries in World War II, Volume II; The British Commonwealth''. 2006: Trafford Publishing, [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. {{ISBN|141208567-5}}.\n* Gen Sir [[Martin Farndale]], ''History of the Royal Regiment of Artillery: The Years of Defeat: Europe and North Africa, 1939\u20131941'', Woolwich: Royal Artillery Institution, 1988/London: Brasseys, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85753-080-2}}.\n* Nicholas Rankin, ''Defending the Rock: How Gibraltar Defeated Hitler'', London: Faber & Faber, 2017, {{ISBN|978-0-571-30770-8}}.\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1944]]\n[[Category:Air defence brigades of the British Army]]\n[[Category:Gibraltar]]\n[[Category:Gibraltar in World War II]]\n[[Category:Anti-Aircraft brigades of the British Army in World War II]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Typo fixing, replaced: Stationary Office \u2192 Stationery Office", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/15th_Anti-Aircraft_Brigade_(United_Kingdom)"}
